supported it by all kinds of repressive legislating such as preventive detention under which opponents of the system and its arbitrary rule were subjected to incarceration for long periods without trial. 
\par <#/>(iii) In 1974-75 whole peasant communities in r
ural Tanzania were uprooted from their traditional homelands and villages by force and dumped into new settlements without proper planning of the new areas where they were left to fend for themselves. <#/>Under this programme, commonly known as villagisat
ion, large peasant communities were suddenly impoverished, and reduced to a state of despair and humiliation. 
\par <#/>(iv)The economy of Tanzania has suffered very badly from such <-/illconceived> policies which were executed without regard to the possible effect on the lives of the people and their welfare. 
\par <#/>(v) On a number of occasions University students were sent home when they complained about poor campus and living conditions, and the quality of education and inadequate facilities. 
\par <#/>2. In many respects the situation inside Tanzania has had many <-/remniscences> of the former colonial regime. 
\par <#/>3. Today, agents of the ruling party are going around the country intimidating the rural population by stories to the effect that the country's peace and 
stability is being threatened by proponents of multi-party system. <#/>The aim of this propaganda is to discredit Multi-partyism so that the existing political status quo can be maintained. <#/>But we are now sure that Tanzanians are fully aware of the pr
e
sent political realities in their country; they want an immediate end to one party hegemony and the return of democracy and a sovereign parliament. <#/>We have said this many times and want to speak even louder through the newly formed Union for Multi-par
ty Democracy shall deter UMD and the people of this peace loving country from their desire to run their affairs and to rid themselves of the repressive rule of the one party state. 
\par <#/>4. Join us now in the union for Multi-party Democracy to help bring new freedom and economic development for our people. 
\par <#/>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 <h> 2. The Constitution of Tanzania </h>
\par }{\fs24\lang2057 <#/>Since independence, Tanzania has never had a constitution that draws its legitimacy from the will and authority of the people in 1961, Westminster imposed t
he independence constitution Tanganyika in 1962 the Republic on constitution which was not referred to the people but was passed by a legislature elected on a limited franchise was yet another imposition. <#/>The 1965 interim constitution was a result of 
T
ANU's decision to impose one-party rule and to provide for the Union Government which was decided by then president of Tanganyika and Zanzibar, Julius Nyerere and Abeid Aman Karume. <#/>Similarly the 1977 constitution was the product of the merger between
 TANU and ASP and was imposed on the people of Tanzania by the newly formed one party - CCM. 
\par <#/>We now say enough is enough and we can not longer accept such dictatorial regimes in Tanzania. <#/>We demand that CCM and its government do convene a national 
constitutional conference to discuss and work on the future Constitution of Tanzania which shall guarantee the sovereignty of parliament and establish truly democratic institutions of the people based on the fundamental human rights of association and ass
embly. 
\par <#/>Articles 3 and 10 of the present constitution impose supremacy of the state party over parliament. <#/>These provisions have usurped the will and power of the people and we demand that immediate action be taken to remove them from the constituti
on even before the promulgation of the national constitution. 
\par <#/>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 <h> 3. Our Independence </h>
\par }{\fs24\lang2057 <#/>During their forty years of rule, the British did not, as a matter of policy, encourage the people 
to form and develop their own free civil societies and organisations to promote their economic, political and social interests or safeguard the terms and conditions of their employment, as workers and civil servants. <#/>Endless volume of legislation to c
ontrol and suppress the people were passed by the legislative council in which the indigenous population was not represented by election until the last five years of British rule. 
\par <#/>This <-/sate> of affairs has not changed since independence in 1961. <#/>In fact, as far as freedom of association and assembly is concerned, the situation has become worse since the one party state was imposed. 
\par <#/>The one party state abolished the right of the people to form freely free cooperative societies and free women'
s and parent's associations. <#/>In fact all important citizen's associations and organization were brought to control of the state party. <#/>Control of the state party. <#/>Further, the one party state has partially disenfranchised most citizens who can
 only vote for candidates nominated by the one party but they themselves are debarred by the constitution from offering their candidature. 
\par <#/>Therefor these thirty years of our independence have seen no real development of free democratic institutions. <#/>The people have been deliberately kept in the dark about their constitutional and basic human rights. 
\par <#/>The efforts to keep the people ign
orant of their basic human rights which include among others the rights to form political parties of their choice are still continuing. <#/>One obvious example is the Presidential Commission on the multi-party Democracy. <#/>The Government has not been ho
n
est enough to tell the people that the right to form political parties is a fundamental right which is already provided for in the constitution under article 20 but the exercise of that right equally by all citizens is denied by articles 3 and 10 which re
serve that right for the enjoyment of the select class of rulers who are members of the state party. 
\par <#/>Soon after our Independence Tanganyika played host to nationals of others African Countries who came as freedom fighters and refugees who had to flee from tyrannical rule in their own countries. 
\par <#/>Tanganyika was proud to use her newly gained independence to Champion the cause of freedom for all Africans who were still under the yoke of the colonial powers. 
\par <#/>Tanganyika, however, misused its Indepen
dence when it began to deploy its military forces to take sides in disputes which were purely internal matters of her neighbours in gambles of unclear political goals. <#/>We in the UMD want to assure our neighbours that we harbour no ambitions of becomin
g a military power for reasons other than defence of our territory. <#/>We want to say categorically, "Never again shall our military forces be deployed outside our borders except under international treaty obligations."
\par }{\fs24\lang2057 <#/>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 <h> 4. The Armed Forces </h>
\par }{\fs24\lang2057 <#
/>We believe that a grave mistake was made by TANU and CCM in involving the country's armed forces into politics. <#/>UMD's position is categorically opposed to a politicised army as we believe that a professional defence force should have no role to play
 in any active politics but must concentrate on training in the use of its equipment and must be ready to serve the country and use its expertise in the defence of the country under any Government of the day with undivided loyalty. 
\par <#/>UMD will therefore advocate a policy which will aim at the complete depoliticisation of all our armed forces. <X_>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 <#/>
Under UMD the armed forces will be supplied and <-/equiped> with the most modern weaponry the country can afford. UMD will take pride to see that our armed forces enjoy the best conditions of service. }{\fs24\lang2057 
\par }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <h> 5. Regional Administration </h>
\par }{\v\fs24\lang2057 At independence Tanganyika was <-/dvided> into nine provinces. The TANU/CCM government has subdivided the provinces into twenty regions. We believed that to allow for more participa
tion by the people in their government the former Provincial administrations should reinstituted, elevated to provide for the creation of semi-autonomous provinces with their legislature with powers to raise revenue to finance their development projects. 
This will mean that we revert to the nine provinces on the lines of former provincial boundaries. This arrangement presupposes the formation of a federal administrative structure at the centre. UMD will welcome public views on this proposal.
\par We believe this
 arrangement will allow the people more say in their local affairs and therefor more democratisation in the country. We strongly believe that by involving the people at this level in the management of their affairs through their own freely elected bodies,
 
the economic development of the country will receive a new impetus. This Provincial Legislature should also have responsibility for District and Urban councils within their boundaries. This change will return local government to the people where it rightl
y belongs and away from CCM which is an intruder in these local affairs.
\par }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <h> 6. The Autonomous Status of Zanzibar </h>
\par }{\v\fs24\lang2057 Zanzibar received her independence in December 1963. Her sovereignty was recognized by the United Nations soon thereafter. The independent
 Republic of Zanzibar was united with the Republic of Tanganyika in April 1964 to form the United Republic of Tanzania under an interim constitution. A permanent constitution was promulgated in 1977 and the country was renamed Tanzania.
\par In recent years bot
h the people of Zanzibar and Tanganyika have shown critical reservations on the form which the union has now taken since the two countries were united. It is of paramount importance that the question of the union, which it is desirable that it be preserve
d
, should be reexamined objectively in the proposed Constitution Conference to arrive at a solution amicable to both parties to the union. There is no doubt that any union of peoples, like a marriage, must be based on trust and mutual consent if it is to l
ast and function smoothly.
\par The union for Multiparty Democracy would support a solution of this important issue on the basis of self determination by both Zanzibar and Tanganyika which has enough reason to grumble since she lost autonomy to the union by comi
ng directly under the administration of the union Government and its former sovereign status was entirely abolished.
\par }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <h> 7. The Civil Service. </h>
\par }{\v\fs24\lang2057 Tanzania inherited an elaborate and efficient civil service from the British Colonial government. A civil se
rvice Commission was responsible for recruitment, training and promotion of all senior staff, a duty it discharged with impartiality and dedication. The civil service was insulated from the politics of the country and served loyally the government of the 
day.
\par We admire the old traditions of a Civil service, insulated from politics because an impartial and dedicated Civil Service could provided a stabilizing influence in a multi-party setting. A well coordinated training program for civil servants is necessa
ry in order to enhance discipline and efficiency.
\par UMD believes that to achieve the ideals of any civil service fair and adequate terms and conditions of service as to salaries and retirement benefits must be devised and kept under constant review.
\par }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <h> 8. Education </h>
\par }{\v\fs24\lang2057 
When provincial administrations are reorganized as it is proposed it will be the duty of provincial legislature to budget for education from primary up to secondary level. This will reduce expenditure on travel and transportation for pupils s
tudying in distant places.
\par We intend to examine in detail, prospects for the reintroduction of intermediate education of the old middle schools. We believe that an extended level of primary education could provided an enlightened population needed in advan
cing rural development. Once primary and secondary education become the responsibility of provincial governments, the Central Government will examine and improve facilities for university education and higher technical training in order to devise programs
 of expansion to cater for a constantly increasing student population. The field of science and technology must undoubtedly receive special attention.
\par }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <h> 9. Freedom of Religion and Worship </h>
\par }{\v\fs24\lang2057 Over the years Tanzania has established a real culture of tole
rance between people of different religious faiths and various denominations. Not only have we had this tolerance, we have also had cooperation between believers of different <-/religious> who have lived together as brothers and sisters. 
\par UMD pledges itself to preserve this feeling of fraternity and shall always promote and allow freedom of worship as one of the most fundamental rights of all Tanzanians, irrespective of their believe and religious affiliations.
\par UMD wishes to warn those mongers of cheap politics who even now speak of the possibility of religious hostility and tribal friction when a Multi Party System is reintroduced, as it certainly shall be.
\par UMD wishes to tell this false prophets of doom that our people know their religious believes well enough as no religion preaches hatred against one's neighbours, on the contrary it <-/teachers> love among <-/manking>.
\par UMD believes that the machination of these false prophets will be entirely defeated.
\par }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <h> 10. Economic Development </h>
\par }{\v\fs24\lang2057 
Tanzania's economic development has stagnated during the 1980's when agricultural production declined badly and capacity utilisation in industry declined to an all time low. This failure to sustain the progress of the 1970's can be attributed to the wrong
 policies of the Arusha Declaration which had disastrous effects on the country's agricultural and industrial production.
\par UMD believes that the freedom available to the people in a Multi-party system to organise themselves for productive purpose with their 
own initiative and cooperative endeavours for production and marketing of their crops without the present interference and controls from the government should a long way to increasing the surplus wealth the country needs for as development capital. 

\par The pe
ople must be allowed to improve their own welfare and the government should only provide the necessary leadership and infrastructure. The present regime siphons off too much of the people's wealth through excessive taxation and levies on the crops by usin
g statutory Marketing Board, which is a very expensive <-/middlement>.
\par In commerce and industry UMD will wish to see the encouragement of private enterprise. There is no doubt at all that in the era which is opening now there is no place for the wasteful pa
rastatals which have through mismanagement cost Tanzania much needed capital for investment. UMD will therefor wish to see closure of all parastatals which are making losses year after year.
\par We believe in developing industries which use mostly our-own raw 
materials to produce goods for our internal market in order to avoid importation of foreign goods which are almost invariably more expensive. We hasten to warn that quality must be the hallmark of production not only for export but also for our local mark
et. It is futile to expect our local market to accept shoddy goods at prices which are higher or even <-/competative> with imported goods. 
\par We must also aim at the export market event if for a start we export semi-finished goods using our raw material. For example, we should export a part of our Cotton crop in the form of yarn or shirt material and other Cotton fabrics and tailored garments.

\par UMD has an open door policy for both public and private investments. We would warmly welcome overseas private investme
nt particularly in agriculture, industry and housing. We will examine our system of taxation with a view to providing tax relief in large scale expatriate investments. We will encourage development in partnership between local and expatriate investors in 
order to raise the level of expertise of our nationals in scientific and high-technology undertakings. It will be a declared policy of UMD to allow overseas investors to expatriate their problem. 
\par The problem of tax-evasion and economic sabotage will be studied thoroughly and steps taken to curb thefts and wilful negligence.
\par }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <h> 11 Transport and Communications </h>
\par }{\v\fs24\lang2057 To facilitate economic development the country will have to put greater emphasis in the provision of all weather roads throughout the whole count
ry. Tanzania does not as yet have network of railways to facilitate the evacuation of crops from areas of production to the urban areas where food crops }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <+_are>}{\v\fs24\lang2057  needed.
\par The railways which are available were designed by the Colonial Regime for the purpose o
f transporting agricultural products intended for export to the metropolitan country where they were needed as raw materials for industries in the country of the colonial power.
\par These railways therefor hardly served the need to open up new areas of production or to provide transport to the regions of the country which produce the bulk of our agricultural products.
\par This does not mean that our railways should be neglected as they are now and left to fall in a state of disrepair. UMD would see to it that our railways are properly maintained.
\par Since the cost of building new railways is far beyond the financial resources available to us at the present time. UMD's policy will be to develop inter regional roads of an all weather standard and bitumenised trunk roads 
to connect with similar inter territorial roads in neighbouring countries and <-/particulary> those territories of our neighbours who are landlocked.
\par Due attention will also be paid to the development of telecommunication as these are vital facilitating rapid communication in commercial circles within the country and overseas among the business community.
\par One factor which militates against the provision of adequate transport facilities in Tanzania today is the very heavy burden of taxation which the transpo
rt industry carries. Transport equipment such as motor vehicles and ancillary equipment carry very high important duty, Sales Tax and <-/licencing> fees to the extent that the ordinary investor is no longer attracted in putting his money in the transport 
business. In a country like Tanzania which relies mostly on road transport these high taxes are counter productive.
\par UMD will wish to examine these fiscal policies very critically as we will certainly want to devise proper schemes of road maintenance to keep our road on a good state of repair.
\par }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <h> 12. Tourism </h>
\par }{\v\fs24\lang2057 One important industry which does not appear to receive adequate Government attention and the necessary budgetary provision to improve its infrastructure is tourism.
\par Tanzania is favoured with almost unlimited natural attractions which would improve it to be a wonderland to the tourist.
\par Apart from our rich Wildlife we have such wonders as the Ngorongoro Crater, Snow-Capped Kilimanjaro situated almost in the equator and the expansive silversands on our beaches. Few countries can boast of such tourist attraction. 
\par It will therefore be our policy to promise the necessary access roads to these areas and hotels and cottages to provide <-/accomodation> to those foreigners who wish to come to see our country 
and enjoy this wonderful heritage of which Tanzania can rightly be proud.
\par If properly managed and encouraged by expert promotion both at home and overseas in tourism is a real gold mine for Tanzania and can generate the foreign exchange which our country needs so badly.
\par UMD will therefor spare no effort to develop this industry which with a relatively small capital expenditure can bring unmeasureable advantages to our economy.
\par }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <h> 13 Housing </h>
\par }{\v\fs24\lang2057 Town planning, the essence of urban development, will receive
 priority. We shall have to see to it that nobody intending to build a house fails to do so on account of having no plot in our towns. The role of the National Housing Cooperation will be encouraged to devise a development plan that will facilitate joint 
ventures with private capital.
\par UMD will encourage urban local authorities to establish housing estates for town dwellers both as tenant purchase schemes and for rental purposes.
\par }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <h> 14 Social Services </h>
\par }{\v\fs24\lang2057 With the decline of agricultural and Industrial production in the 1980's provision of social services of health, water and education suffered a setback from the progress recorded in the 1970's.
\par The idea of a welfare state is entici
ng. But the extension of social services can only come from the fruits of an expanded economy. We shall endeavour aid for orphans disabled and aged people. We shall look into the possibility of instituting effective administration of projects, both offici
a
l and private, to guarantee the welfare of disabled people and orphaned children. The <-/extention> of facilities for youth activities including sports will be <-/sriously> undertaken. Generally, all social services in health and medicare with </OM> have 
been in decline these years will be revamped as the economy is resuscitated and revenues become more available. 
\par }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <h> 15 Land and Land Use </h>
\par }{\v\fs24\lang2057 Tanzania is free from land hunger; and fertile valleys and plains are awaiting development. Given a dynamic leader
ship, and proper land use planning in Tanzania can become an agricultural and forest wonderland. UMD will examine in depth the law governing ownership of land with a view to facilitate large-scale estate agriculture. Our banks and finance institutions wil
l be encouraged to provide loans to farmers. Expatriate finance will be attracted in joint agricultural ventures with <-/indegenous> farmers to raise their level of performance in the agricultural industry using fertile land which is in great abundance.

\par A close study will be undertaken to assess the viability of current irrigation projects and where possible to enhance their performance, and extend the area of irrigated land by using water from our rivers and lakes.
\par }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <h> 16 Trade Unions and the Workers </h>
\par }{\v\fs24\lang2057 W
e recognize the right of the workers to associate themselves freely in trade union organizations so that to restore collective bargaining between employers and workers. In this way we <-_the> believe workers will be enabled to play their full role in indu
strial development. Leading to greater industrial production.
\par The right to strike is an indispensable weapon of free trade unionism. We shall encourage trade unions to use the strike weapon only as the last resort when the machinery set up to regulate labour relations has <-/exhausitively> been applied.
\par We stand for the independence of trade unions and will always reject the idea of affiliating worker organisations with political parties. Tanzania's labour movement lost its independent existence when TANU de
stroyed the Tanganyika Federation of Labour on the mainland and the Afro-Shirazi Party abolished the Zanzibar Federation of Labour on the islands early in 1964. We intend to work towards the restoration of the independence of the labour movement.
\par }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <h> 17 The Co-operative Movement </h>
\par }{\v\fs24\lang2057 Before independence, and soon afterwards, Tanzania boasted of having one of the finest cooperative systems on the African Continent. There was the long <-/astablished> and celebrated Kilimanjaro Native Cooperative Union of Mosh
i which was instrumental in the development of Coffee growing and marketing by the Wachaga.
\par A similar Cooperative Organisation existed in Bukoba which served the Robusta Coffee growers in the West Lake area. In the years just before independence the Cotton
 growers of Sukumaland set up the Nyanza Federation of Cooperative Union based on Cotton growing.
\par All these Cooperative Unions were organised on a voluntary basis by the people themselves with a minimum of control of the central Government which only provi
ded expert advice to assist the movement. It was therefor an event which caused much dismay and sorrow to see these organisations of the people seized and their property sequestrated in the aftermath of the ill-conceived Arusha Declaration of 1967.
\par With this sad background in mind we in UMD fully recognise the right of our farmers and peasants to freely organise their <-/corporative> societies without any government interference other than a minimum of regulatory powers of inspection. 
\par UMD will therefore en
courage the development of <-/trully> free and independent cooperative unions. We have observed that even the recent changes in cooperative legislation there is still unwarranted control through the apex organisation which like OTTU in the trade union mov
ement is an imposition on people's organisation which should be entirely free from those who are not themselves members of the farming community.}{\fs24\lang2057  </I>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
