\par <I> <h> Guidelines on the law: Can High Court end corporal punishment? </h>
\par }{\b\fs24\lang2057 <#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 THE USE of corporal punishment has a long history. <#/>In recent years the use of this type of punishment has brought a hot discussion all over the world. 
\par <#/>Mixed feelings about the use of corporal punishment have existed among various groups. 
\par <#/>We in Tanzania are not free from this controversial debate on corporal punishment and the social conflicts resulting from it. 
\par <#/>In our day to day life, some parents administer corporal punishment as a means of control children's behaviour. 
\par <#/>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 In Tanzania, corporal punishment still exists in our statute books and it is governed by the Corporal Punishment Ordinance Chapter 17. 
\par <#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 Most of European countries with the exception of the United Kingdom, Denmark and Switzerland had abolished this type of punishment. 
\par <#/>Each Nation has its own method of dealing with criminals. 
\par <#/>However, there is always a room for learning better ways from others and making reforms whenever a need arise. 
\par <#/>Before we go deep into the issue let's first <-/conceptulize> what is punishment. 
\par <#/>Punishment is a reaction intended to deprive the punished something the punisher assume is valued. 
\par <#/>However, punishment is a relative thing in the sense that what is deprivation for one person or group of <-_person><+_persons> may not be for another. 
\par <#/>Different people have different views regarding which deprivation is more severe than the other. 
\par <#/>The major theories which have been developed over the ages <-_includes><+_include> retribution, deterrence and reformation. 
\par <#/>The essence of }{\b\fs24\lang2057 Retribution Theory}{\fs24\lang2057  is that the punishment should fit the crime. 
\par <#/>Many people believe that retribution is revenge. 
\par <#/>However, others believe that retribution is not a revenge but it is a theory which holds the suffering of a man as a result of his own act, for a bad act is bound to meet suffering. 
\par <#/>It is agreed that the theory of retribution <-/foruses> upon the offence rather than offender because in essence the punishment should fit the crime. 
\par <#/>This theory was an improvement from the primitive stage where practically all crime were punished }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <&/>grammar}{\v\fs24\lang2057  }{\fs24\lang2057 with extreme harshness. 
\par <#/>For example, cutting off the hands of thief in order to disable him from stealing. 
\par <#/>Retribution hence is opposed to any scientific approach which aims at the individual <-_deliquency><+_delinquent> and <-_intend><+_intends> to deter him from further <-/deliquency>. 
\par <#/><-_Other><+_Others> <-_holds><+_hold> that this theory <-_deter><+_deters> the criminal himself from committing the same offence and also <-_deter><+_deters> the general public so as to be a lesson to other potential criminals within the society. 

\par <#/>That is, the criminal intending to commit a crime will have to think twice before he decides to act. 
\par <#/>Reformation as a punishment may mean that the offender is reformed while being punished or that he is reformed by the punishment itself qua the punishment. 
\par <#/>Some penologists believe that punishment can reform an offender. 
\par <#/>It is however noted that reformation of the offender is no way conflicting with that of retribution. 
\par <#/>Dr. James Seth, one of the famous <-_writer><+_writers> on this issue, postulates that theories of punishment are inter-dependent and are not mutually exclusive. 
\par <#/>Some writers have provided a very useful way to picture penalty types by enumerating four principle methods of punishment. 
\par <#/>In 1963, for the first time just after our independence, the first }{\b\fs24\lang2057 Minimum Sentence Act}{\fs24\lang2057  justified the application of corporal punishment. 
\par <#/>Tabling the bill before the Parliament, the then Vice President, <ea/>Ndugu Rashidi Kawawa stated categorically that: 
\par "}{\b\fs24\lang2057 To consider corporal punishment
 is an unpleasant thing for any civilized person to do, but we have to make people recognize that to commit an offence against the nation or any of its <-_citizen><+_citizens> is an evil thing which is a disgrace to the man who does it. 
\par <#/>"When this attitude is adopted generally, then we should be in a position to revise our method of dealing with offenders but until then we can have no mercy.}{\fs24\lang2057 "
\par }{\b\fs24\lang2057 <#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 Immediately after passing the bill criticism were voiced }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <&/>grammar}{\fs24\lang2057  from various groups. 
\par <#/>Writers like Cole and Denison referred it as a "draconian measure which fails to achieve a significant reduction in the incidence of the type of offences at which it is aimed at. 
\par <#/>In a paper presented on criminology at the University of Dar es Salaam, the punishment was vigorously criticized: the paper reacted that: }{\b\fs24\lang2057 
\par "The main objectives of corporal punishment is that it is degrading to those who must partake, particularly the <-_applies><+_appliers>}{\fs24\lang2057  }{\b\fs24\lang2057 
and the applied, and to the society generally, there is no justification of treating human beings in a manner which is essentially <-/in human>, in that, it is an infliction of physical harm rather than appeal to reason."
\par }{\b\fs24\lang2057 <#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 P.T. Georges, the then Chief Justice addressing the issue of punishment generally said in his own words that: 
\par "}{\b\fs24\lang2057 Certainly my initial reaction to punishments here was that they were on the whole too severe and needed moderation. 
\par <#/>"This is still my reaction though by the passage of time has made me <-/some what> less positive about it than I was at first.}{\fs24\lang2057 "
\par }{\b\fs24\lang2057 <#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 Corporal punishment is a manifestation of anger rather than reason and it is rather the primitive form of punishment which <-_serve><+_serves> no useful purpose. 
\par <#/>Tanner, one of the writers who studied South African penology and the use of corporal punishment concluded that: 
\par "}{\b\fs24\lang2057 The figures for corporal punishment administered and persons prosecuted over the same period show very clear that whatever other reasons there may have been, this legislation certainly did not have the intended effect.}{\fs24\lang2057 
"
\par }{\b\fs24\lang2057 <#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 An attempt to denounce corporal punishment in our society was made in 1971 when late Ndugu Maswnya, the Minister of Home Affairs, held a press conference and said that: 
\par "}{\b\fs24\lang2057 Corporal punishment was unsocialistic and that it had failed because crimes was in the increase. 
\par <#/>"I call upon the public to express their views on the
\par abolition of compulsory canning under our Minimum Sentence Act. 
\par <#/>"Discuss the issue on seminars, people's organs and the press (emphasis added)}{\fs24\lang2057 ."
\par }{\fs24\lang2057 <#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 In 1972, a bill was submitted to the parliament to abolish corporal punishment. 
\par <#/>The government admitted openly that corporal punishment had brought hostility towards the Party, government and was contrary to the whole idea of reformation. 
\par <#/>In fact, earlier on, the government said that there was a reported increase in crime which showed that the flogging deterrent had failed, although it did not explain why it attributed such a failure to corporal punishment. 
\par <#/>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 In the 1972 Minimum Sentence Act Bill}{\fs24\lang2057 , corporal punishment was abolished and the Act came into force on 1st May,1972. 
\par <#/>As noted above, the new Act did away with corporal punishment and instead, minimum and maximum periods of imprisonment were increased for property offences. 
\par <#/>Today corporal punishment is governed under the }{\b\fs24\lang2057 Corporal Punishment Ordinance chapter 17. 
\par <#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 Under Section 2 of the Act Corporal Punishment is defined to mean whipping in the case of an adult and <-_canning><+_caning> in the case of a juvenile. 
\par <#/>This type of punishment is only restricted to some extent. 
\par <#/>To show how the courts interpreted and applied the law, it is better to cite here the case of }{\b\fs24\lang2057 R.V. Musa Yusufa (1970) HCD 308. 
\par <#/>In this case the court held very strongly that: " ...Despite of his <-/youth fulness}{\fs24\lang2057 >}{\b\fs24\lang2057 
 and coupled with the fact that he is a first offender, he is liable, to the statutory two years imprisonment and will also receive twenty four strokes as a corporal punishment. <#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 "
\par <-/Morover>, corporal punishment was allowed in our }{\b\fs24\lang2057 Education Act, 1978}{\fs24\lang2057  to be administered in schools by teachers. 
\par <#/>The Act provides, among other things, that the Minister of Education is empowered by the Act to make regulations for the administering }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <&/>grammar}{\fs24\lang2057  corporal punishment in schools. 
\par <#/>Holding that whipping was cruel and <-/unsual> punishment, the supreme court of America was of the view that the scope of amendment of any law is not static but "must draw its meaning from the evolving standards of decency that mar
k progress of maturity society."
\par }{\fs24\lang2057 <#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 The main causes of crime is }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <&/>grammar}{\fs24\lang2057  to be found in the socio-economic set up of the country. 
\par <#/>However, the forms of treatment and intention for which they are administered vary a great deal. 
\par <#/>Most researches conducted in Tanzania clearly shows }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <&/>grammar}{\fs24\lang2057 
 that most crimes which are said to have been committed are those related to property showing that our society is undergoing stratification and thereby gradual creating rich and poor people. 
\par <#/>Poverty alone does not force a person to commit crime, but it does produce the condition most conducive for <-/cime> commission. 
\par <#/>Today, many countries put more emphasis on understanding the offender and the root cause of the offence rather than only punishing the offender. 
\par <#/>This new approach <-_help><+_helps> a great deal in re-educating the offender for reformation. 
\par <#/>Therefore, while we accept that punishment can hold social reforms, we must also bear in mind the dangers of applying it. 
\par <#/>Under, Article 13 (b)(e) of the }{\b\fs24\lang2057 Constitution of the United Republic of Tanzania}{\fs24\lang2057  it is clearly provided that: 
\par "}{\b\fs24\lang2057 No person shall be subjected to <-/tourture>}{\fs24\lang2057  o}{\b\fs24\lang2057 r to <-/in human> or degrading treatment.}{\fs24\lang2057 "
\par }{\b\fs24\lang2057 <#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 The authority which is highly persuasive for the protection from <-/in human> or degrading punishments is that which was delivered in the Supreme Court of Zimbabwe in }{\b\fs24\lang2057 (1978) 2 EH RR/I}{
\fs24\lang2057 . 
\par <#/>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 In this case the issue before the Supreme Court was whether Section 54(5)(C) and 54(8) of the Magistrate Court Act became unconstitutional and of no force. 
\par <#/>Also whether those sections violated the protection from <-/in human> or degrading punishment as provided for in Article 15(1) of the Constitution of Zimbabwe. 
\par <#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 A full bench of the Supreme Court of Zimbabwe declared the imposition of the strokes to be constitutional and therefore void and of no effect. 
\par <#/>They said the sentence of whipping is likely to generate hatred against the prison regime in particular and the system of justice in general. 
\par <#/>In the famous case of }{\b\fs24\lang2057 Chumchua Marwa v. Officer I/C of Musoma Prison & A.G.}{\fs24\lang2057  which attempted to declare the Deportation Ordinance to be unconsti
tutional and therefore void and no effect Judge Mwalusanya states that: "}{\b\fs24\lang2057 The doctrine of rule of law becomes betrayal of the individual if the laws themselves are not fair but are oppressive and degrading}{\fs24\lang2057 . 
\par <#/>Therefore it remains to be seen if the High Court of Tanzania which had been empowered under Article 30(3) of the }{\b\fs24\lang2057 constitution of United Republic}{\fs24\lang2057 
 to declare any law to be unconstitutional and therefore void and of no effect, could declare Corporal Punishment Ordinance chapter 17 as infringing the basic rights protected by our constitution. </I>
