\par <I> <h> CONSENT IN RAPE AS LAW PROVIDES </h>
\par }{\fs24\lang2057 <#/>}{\fs24 RAPE is, among, the offences which are against morality. 
\par <#/>It is covered under Section 130 of the Penal Code. <#/>The Section provides that:
\par }{\b\fs24 Any person who has unlawful carnal knowledge of a woman or girl, without her consent, or with her consent, if the consent is obtained by force or by means of threats or intimidation of any kind, or by fear of <-/b
odly> harm, or by means of false representations as to the nature of the act, or, in the case of a married woman, by <-/personating> her husband, is guilty of the felony termed "rape". 
\par <#/>}{\fs24 It is apparent from this quoted Section that the offence <-_at> is committed when a man does sexual intercourse with a woman, without her consent. 
\par <#/>The referred to consent here is free and conscious permission of the woman to the act of sexual intercourse. 
\par <#/>That is she should be free to permit the act to be done upon her body. 
\par <#/>She should not be forced to the act. 
\par <#/>Thus, the most vital elements to be proved by the prosecution side on the charge of rape is lack of consent on the part of the woman and penetration of male's genital organ into that of a woman. 
\par <#/>Failure by the prosecution to prove either of these, the offence of rape can not be said to have been committed. 
\par <#/>For purposes of this discussion, the element of consent is analysed into details. 
\par <#/>However, those wishing to familiarise themselves with "rape" in general may refer to my article }{\i\fs24 Rape}{\fs24  which appeared in the }{\i\fs24 Sunday News}{\fs24  of 28/5/1989. 
\par <#/>Consent to the act of sexual intercourse can be obtained from the woman directly or indirectly. 
\par <#/>By directly we mean that the woman may speak openly that she is ready for the act. 
\par <#/>Whereas by indirectly we mean that she may remain silent, yet offers herself to the man. 
\par <#/>That is why there is a common saying that "silence means consent". 
\par <#/>With this, the material circumstances surrounding, the case will be the guiding points. 
\par <#/>For example, delay, in reporting rape can, in a fit case, make the court <-/presure> that the woman consented to the act. 
\par <#/>To illustrate this, let us see what happened in the case of }{\i\fs24 Nazir and Zulfiker v.R}{\fs24  (1970) HCD 2177. 
\par <#/>In this case appellants were convicted of rape. <#/>The appellants struck a friendship with the complainant. 
\par <#/>One day they drove her to Karanga Bridge in Moshi and raped her in turn. 
\par <#/>The Medical Officer found no marks of violence on any part of Miss Lykstedt's body. 
\par <#/>The appellant, Zulfiker denied having had sexual intercourse with her while appellant Nazir agreed that he had intercourse with Miss Lykstedt with her consent. 
\par <#/>While allowing the appeal and quashing convictions, Platt J., stated that:
\par }{\b\fs24 "The issue between consent and force was narrow.... 
\par <#/>"The background of the case did not allow any clear view that Miss Berit would certainly not have agreed to sexual intercourse with the appellants. 
\par <#/>"She was a woman of 27 years of age, and on her own admission used to having sexual intercourse, at least in Sweden. 
\par <#/>"Although she had another "boy friend" at the time, she agreed to meet Liaquat. 
\par <#/>"She had put herself in the hands of young men both Liaquat and Nazir being 21 years of age, and Zulfiker still younger. 
\par <#/>However that maybe, all three men were much younger than Miss Berit}{\fs24 . 
\par <#/>}{\b\fs24 "From these facts, it could well be suggested that she was as likely to <
-_the><+_have> consented to sexual intercourse as that she had not, and the learned magistrate's points that she came from "a permissive society" does not seem wide of the mark". 
\par <#/>}{\fs24 His lordship did not end there. <#/>He continued to observe:
\par }{\b\fs24 "The evidence then appears to me to have been <-/equivocall> as to the likelihood of her consent. 
\par <#/>She did not make any complaint when help was first at hand at the Mission. 
\par <#/>"In my view the evidence relied upon by ... the learned magistrate concerning her report and later antagonism towards the appellants did not necessarily show that her allegations}{\fs24  }{\b\fs24 were true". 
\par <#/>}{\fs24 Likewise, consent may be presumed from a complainant who was too drunk to resist. 
\par <#/>Substantially this was the holding in the case of }{\i\fs24 Mchelengwanjingi Masala}{\fs24  v R (1968) HCD 370. 
\par <#/>Four accused were in this case convicted of rape contrary to Section 130 of the Penal Code. 
\par <#/>There was evidence that the accused and the complainant had been drinking together and that all of them were drunk. 
\par <#/>At about midnight, one of the accused carried complainant away. 
\par <#/>Complainant testified that the first and second accused then had intercourse with her by force. 
\par <#/>She stated that the third and fourth accused later had intercourse with her but that she was too tired and drunk by that time to resist. 
\par <#/>Another prosecution witness saw the third accused having intercourse with complainant, and a torn piece of her clothing was later found near the scene. 
\par <#/>The first and third accused admitted having had intercourse with complainant but stated that she had consented. 
\par <#/>The second and fourth accused denied having had intercourse with her. 
\par <#/>It was held, among other things, that there may be authority supporting conviction for rape when the complainant is too drunk, to resist. 
\par <#/>However, the court continued, in the present case, there is no corroboration of complainant's testimony that the intercourse with the first and third accused was without her consent. 
\par <#/>Neither the torn clothing nor the fact that she was drunk would necessarily negative the fact of her consent. 
\par <#/>Seaton J. continued to hold further that the trial magistrate also failed to consider the possibility that because of their drunkenness the accused had no intention to commit rape and mistakenly believed that complainant had consented. 
\par <#/>To that effect the court quashed the conviction. 
\par <#/>The <-/aforegoing> two cases show that the charges of rape failed to stand since the circumstances under which sexual intercourses were committed }{\b\v\fs24 <&/>grammar}{\fs24  indicated that the women consented. 
\par <#/>Thus the element of lack of consent in the charges was insufficiently proved. 
\par <#/>However, as the quoted Section of the Penal Code shows, 'there are instances under which consent cannot be said to have been obtained from female parties. 
\par <#/>To outline them, we start with consent initiated by fear for daughter's health. 
\par <#/>This cannot be said to be freely and consciously obtained. 
\par <#/>For there is a necessity for the victim to consent. <#/>This occurred in the case of }{\i\fs24 Mtuniduchile and others versus}{\fs24  R (1970) HCD 204. 
\par <#/>In this case three appellants were convicted of burglary, stealing and rape. 
\par <#/>According to the evidence given by a woman and a daughter, the appellants broke into their house, stole some articles and demanded to have sexual intercourse with the daughter who was in advanced state of pregnancy. 
\par <#/>The mother, fearing for the life of the daughter offered herself instead whereupon each of the appellants had sexual intercourse with her in turn. 
\par <#/>Dismissing the appeal, the late Biron J. stated that:
\par "The two women were alone in the house, which is apparently isolated. 
\par <#/>"They were threatened with death by the three men armed with knives if they tried to raise the alarm. 
\par <#/>"Although the mother consented, in fact volunteered herself as a substitute for her daughter such consent is, to my mind, initiated by her fe
ars for her daughter's health, and it is not irrelevant to note that the Section above set out expressly states that if the consent is obtained 'by fear of bodily harm, the act would still constitute rape. 
\par <#/>"The mother, apart from her maternal affection, was under a duty to protect her daughter, therefore I fully agree, with respect, with the learned magistrate, that the acts of the three <-/acucsed> constituted rape on the part of each. 
\par <#/>"The conviction for rape is therefore duly upheld". 
\par <#/>The position of the law is also to the effect that consent obtained by false representation is no consent at all. 
\par <#/>And hence the charge of rape will stand. 
\par <#/>In substance, this was the holding in the English case of R. versus Williams (1923) 1 K.B.- 340. 
\par <#/>Briefly stated, the facts of this case are as <-/hereunder>:
\par The appellant who was engaged to give lessons in singing and voice production to a girl of sixteen years of age, had sexual intercourse with her under the pretence that her breathing was n
ot quite right and that he had to perform an operation to enable her to produce her voice properly. 
\par <#/>The girl submitted to what was done under the belief, wilfully and fraudulently induced by the <-/apellant>, that she was being medically and surgicall
y treated by the appellant and not with the intention that he should have sexual intercourse with her. 
\par <#/>He was convicted of rape. <#/>The court stated that a consent or submission obtained by fraud, it would not <-_a> be a defence. 
\par <#/>Furthermore, it is equally rape despite the fact that consent is obtained but by false representation in respect of <-/personating> a husband of the complainant. 
\par <#/>This is so observed in the case of }{\i\fs24 R versus Dee}{\fs24  (1884) 15 Cox CC 579. 
\par <#/>In this case after knowing that the husband of the complainant had gone out for fishing, the accused entered in the room of the complainant at or about 9.00 p.m. 
\par <#/>Thinking that the person who entered was her husband, the complainant uttered: "have you come back just now". 
\par <#/>The accused did not reply. <#/>Instead he put off the trousers, jumped into the bed and had sexual <-/intercouse> with the complainant. 
\par <#/>While the act was going on, the complainant learned that the person was not her husband. <#/>The accused was charged with rape. 
\par <#/>Lawson J., held that to rape is to have carnal knowledge of a woman without her consent. 
\par <#/>Therefore a wife who consents to have sexual intercourse with another has not consented if such person had <-/personated> himself a husband of the said wife. 
\par <#/>The accused was convicted of rape. 
\par <#/>To conclude therefore, consent is a very important element in rape cases. 
\par <#/>For its absence means that the victim was forced to have carnally known. 
\par <#/>Whereas its presence is a benefit to the accused person. 
\par <#/>For that matter, lack of consent should be proved by the prosecution. </I>
